This page is a supplementary teaching scaffold for templates, TIR and reactivity.

## Template ownership

AST owns template composition, slot routing, wrapper context, folding and runtime handoff.

One module AST build owns one `TemplateIrStore`. The exact `TirView` is the structural authority.

The lifecycle is:

```text
Parsed -> Composed -> Formatted -> Finalized
```

One preparation owner validates exact views and classifies foldable, runtime and helper structure. Folding and runtime handoff consume the same accepted view.

No TIR store, ID, view, overlay or preparation type crosses into a completed module, HIR or backend.

## Reactivity boundary

Reactivity is a constrained source-and-sink model.

- AST resolves source identities and subscriptions.
- HIR carries target-neutral reactive facts.
- Borrow validation treats subscriptions as read-only dependencies.
- Target validation rejects unsupported reachable forms.
- Runtime update policy belongs to the builder and backend.

## Rewrite focus

Explain why a specialised IR helps templates, how exact views prevent competing authority and how reactive dependency tracking differs from closures and borrows.

Canonical details live in the compiler and memory authorities.
